comments.body:
One way would be to make {{Status::State}} a public type with virtual methods. Since {{Status::state_}} is null in almost all cases, I wouldn't think this would have performance implications (though {{delete state_}} now would require invoking a virtual ctor) but this should be examined more closely (in godbolt) to be sure.

So we could define something like

{code}
class GandivaErrorState : public Status::ErrorState {
 public:
  std::string error_type() const override { return "gandiva"; }
  ...
};
{code}

We could use the status range and the error code within it to get something similar:
{code:java}
enum GandivaErrorCode : int32_t {
  CodeGenError,
  //...
};

static StatusRange GandivaError("gandiva", {
  "CodeGenError",
  //...
});

Status MakeCodeGenError() {
  return GandivaError(CodeGenError, "msg"); // overload call operator to act as a factory
}

void QueryUsage(Status s) {
  s.Is<GandivaError>();               // query category
  s.Is<GandivaError, CodeGenError>(); // query code within category
  // or equivalently
  s.Is(GandivaError);               // query category
  s.Is(GandivaError, CodeGenError); // query code within category
}{code}
